__cs__ But before I go there , please allow me to share with you glimpses of my personal story .
__cs__ I will do so with the help of words , of course , but also a geometrical shape , the circle , so throughout my talk , you will come across several circles .
__cs__ I was born in Strasbourg , France to Turkish parents .
__cs__ Shortly after , my parents got separated , and I came to Turkey with my mom .
__cs__ From then on , I was raised as a single child by a single mother .
__cs__ Now in the early 1970s , in Ankara , that was a bit unusual .
__cs__ Our neighborhood was full of large families , where fathers were the heads of households , so I grew up seeing my mother as a divorcee in a patriarchal environment .
__cs__ In fact , I grew up observing two different kinds of womanhood .
__cs__ On the one hand was my mother , a well-educated , secular , modern , westernized , Turkish woman .
__cs__ On the other hand was my grandmother , who also took care of me and was more spiritual , less educated and definitely less rational .
__cs__ This was a woman who read coffee grounds to see the future and melted lead into mysterious shapes to fend off the evil eye .
__cs__ Many people visited my grandmother , people with severe acne on their faces or warts on their hands .
__cs__ Each time , my grandmother would utter some words in Arabic , take a red apple and stab it with as many rose thorns as the number of warts she wanted to remove .
__cs__ Then one by one , she would encircle these thorns with dark ink .
__cs__ A week later , the patient would come back for a follow-up examination .
__cs__ Now , I &apos;m aware that I should not be saying such things in front of an audience of scholars and scientists , but the truth is , of all the people who visited my grandmother for their skin conditions , I did not see anyone go back unhappy or unhealed .
__cs__ I asked her how she did this . Was it the power of praying ?
__cs__ In response she said , &quot; &quot; Yes , praying is effective , but also beware of the power of circles . &quot; &quot; From her , I learned , amongst many other things , one very precious lesson — that if you want to destroy something in this life , be it an acne , a blemish or the human soul , all you need to do is to surround it with thick walls .
__cs__ It will dry up inside .
__cs__ Now we all live in some kind of a social and cultural circle .
__cs__ We all do .
__cs__ We &apos;re born into a certain family , nation , class .
__cs__ But if we have no connection whatsoever with the worlds beyond the one we take for granted , then we too run the risk of drying up inside .
__cs__ Our imagination might shrink ; our hearts might dwindle , and our humanness might wither if we stay for too long inside our cultural cocoons .
__cs__ Our friends , neighbors , colleagues , family — if all the people in our inner circle resemble us , it means we are surrounded with our mirror image .
__cs__ Now one other thing women like my grandma do in Turkey is to cover mirrors with velvet or to hang them on the walls with their backs facing out .
__cs__ It &apos;s an old Eastern tradition based on the knowledge that it &apos;s not healthy for a human being to spend too much time staring at his own reflection .
__cs__ Ironically , &#91; living in &#93; communities of the like-minded is one of the greatest dangers of today &apos;s globalized world .
__cs__ And it &apos;s happening everywhere , among liberals and conservatives , agnostics and believers , the rich and the poor , East and West alike .
__cs__ We tend to form clusters based on similarity , and then we produce stereotypes about other clusters of people .
